.loadClass(typeName);\n                        } catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {\n                            upperBoundType = null;\n                        }\n                        String rule = lineParts[0].substring(1);\n                        if (rule.equals(\"whitelistPolicyIfAssignable\")) {\n                            if (upperBoundType != null) {\n                                Set<Class<?>> targetSet =\n                                        (upperBoundType.getModifiers() & Modifier.FINAL) != 0\n                                                ? whitelistRuleFinalClasses\n                                                : whitelistRuleNonFinalClasses;\n                                targetSet.add(upperBoundType);\n                            }\n                        } else if (rule.equals(\"blacklistUnlistedMembers\")) {\n                            if (upperBoundType != null) {\n                                typesWithBlacklistUnlistedRule.add(upperBoundType);\n                            }\n                        } else {\n                            throw new IllegalStateException(\"Unhandled rule: \" + rule);\n                        }\n                    } else {\n                        MemberSelector memberSelector;\n                        try {\n                            memberSelector = MemberSelector.parse(line, classLoader);\n                        } catch (ClassNotFoundException | NoSuchMethodException | NoSuchFieldException e) {\n                            // Can happen if we run on an older Java than the list was made for\n                            memberSelector = null;\n\n[92 more lines in file. Use offset=111 to continue.]"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1777643330254}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing JDK 21 changes**\n\nI’m considering potential removed methods in JDK 21, like `Thread.destroy`, and whether it’s been deprecated or is just missing. In static initialization, parsing might throw exceptions if not in development mode, which raises issues with `NoSuchMethod`. I'm thinking about dynamic access with reflect metadata; however, is that too broad? The current reports indicate that missing metadata isn’t the issue. It might be better to use generated test resources to include `unsafeMethods.properties` to avoid native failures.\n\n**Exploring reflective methods**\n\nI'm considering how reflective methods work in parsing, particularly at native runtime. There’s a possibility that Native Image supports `Class#getMethod` for public JDK methods, which I think might be worth risking. I need to create a dedicated test file under `src/test/java` for graalvm-reachability-metadata. Deciding on the test content is key—maybe I'll use `LegacyDefaultMemberAccessPolicy.INSTANCE` and assert that public methods are processed correctly. The challenge is ensuring that the blacklist queries methods in `unsafeMethods` effectively. We could avoid directly calling `getMethod` by using `Object.class.getMethods()`.\n\n**Considering FreeMarker templates**\n\nI’m thinking about whether a FreeMarker template can access a class. It seems I need an object with a method that returns Runtime, and I wonder if static models would help here. The Legacy policy blocks dangerous methods only through the introspector. So, could I configure the BeansWrapper with `LegacyDefaultMemberAccessPolicy` to expose a Class object? I’ll need to verify if templates can access methods. For simplification, maybe using `BeansWrapper wrapper = new BeansWrapper(Configuration.VERSION_2_3_21)` would work and would be legacy by default, but I think the default might change for versions below 2.3.30